<TITLE> Tejgaon workers' protest turns violent </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Feb 23 (bdnews24.com) Garments workers of a Tejgaon factory staged a demonstration on Monday in the wake of an alleged attacks on colleagues. At one stage, the protesting workers of Sunshine Knitwear Ltd locked in a three-hour battle with other workers in the industrial area, said police. "Workers of Sunshine Knitwear were protesting as some of them were beaten up by the local gangsters," acting officer-in-charge of Tejgaon police Shafiqul Islam told bdnews24.com. "When they tried to get other garments factory workers to join with them, clashes broke out. But police eventually brought the situation under control. Some were slightly injured in the clash," said Islam. Faruq, a Sunshine employee, told bdnews24.com: "Workers from another factory beat one of our assistant production managers, and when he complained local gang came and beat up another seven workers." When news of their beaten colleagues reached the Sunshine factory, about 1,700 workers poured out on to the street, said Faruq. They also called on workers of Topaz Garments to join them. "As we were heading to another factory, of Hamim Group, to call on their workers to join us, a group swooped on us with sticks." Police said the latter were Hamim Group workers, while Sunshine workers claimed they were agitators and local gangsters. The clashes, lasting about three hours, saw factory windows and vehicles smashed by brickbats. The police brought the situation under control after some 12 workers were seriously injured in the three-sided battle that included the law enforcers. Sunshine workers were given holiday after the unrest, while police were deployed on site to ward off any untoward incident. bdnews
